3. PERMITTED USES

3.1 Personal Study and Learning

An individual may use the Software for personal, non-commercial study,
learning, experimentation, hobby work, and skills development, provided there
is no anticipated commercial application and no Production Use.

3.2 Education

An individual, accredited educational institution, or non-profit educational
program may use the Software for classroom teaching, coursework, academic
demonstrations, and supervised student projects. This permission does not
cover paid corporate training, professional consulting, or operational use by
the institution.

3.3 Non-Commercial Research

You may use and internally modify the Software for Non-Commercial Research.
You may publish research methods, findings, measurements, and criticism,
provided that You:

(a) identify the exact Software version, commit, and artifact digest used;
(b) clearly distinguish Your findings from any Licensor claim or
    certification;
(c) do not distribute the Software or a modified version;
(d) do not publish a substantial portion of the Software's source code,
    private verifier packs, held-out data, non-public materials, or
    credentials; and
(e) follow Section 4 for vulnerability information.

You may include minimal excerpts or patch fragments reasonably necessary to
explain a result, but not enough to reconstruct a substantial part of the
Software or a restricted verifier pack.

3.4 Time-Limited Evaluation

Any individual or organization may conduct Evaluation Use during the
Evaluation Period only if all of the following are true:

(a) the evaluation occurs in an isolated, non-production environment;
(b) only synthetic, public, or specifically authorized non-production data
    and repositories are used;
(c) no customer, production, confidential third-party, or regulated data is
    processed unless the Licensor gives prior written permission;
(d) the Software and its output are not relied on to make a real merge,
    release, deployment, security, audit, compliance, or business decision;
(e) access is limited to personnel reasonably necessary for the evaluation;
(f) the Software is not exposed as a network service to third parties; and
(g) all use stops when the Evaluation Period ends unless a separate written
    license has been obtained.

3.5 Good-Faith Security Research

Good-faith security research is permitted only as described in Section 4 and
the repository's SECURITY.md file. If the two conflict, the more protective
requirement for third-party systems, data, and coordinated disclosure applies.

4. SECURITY RESEARCH SAFE HARBOR

The Licensor will not assert a copyright-license claim solely against
good-faith security research that fully complies with this Section.

You must:

(a) test only systems, accounts, data, and repositories You own or are
    expressly authorized to test;
(b) avoid privacy violations, data destruction, persistent access,
    extortion, social engineering, denial of service, and unnecessary
    disruption;
(c) access only the minimum data needed to confirm a finding and stop if
    sensitive data is encountered;
(d) report a potentially exploitable vulnerability privately through the
    channel identified in SECURITY.md without unreasonable delay;
(e) provide enough detail to reproduce and remediate the issue;
(f) allow a reasonable coordinated-disclosure period before public
    disclosure, normally up to ninety (90) days unless the parties agree
    otherwise or an urgent public-safety reason requires a different course;
(g) not use the finding for Commercial Use, competitive product development,
    unlawful access, or harm; and
(h) comply with applicable law.

This safe harbor does not authorize testing of third-party services or
infrastructure, does not waive rights of third parties, and does not protect
conduct outside this License.

